announced yet in Japan

00:10:16.390 --> 00:10:18.370
so I think it's a miracle
that I can talk about it

00:10:18.370 --> 00:10:19.900
in a library, of all places.

00:10:19.900 --> 00:10:21.310
&gt;&gt; Maureen Cohen
Harrington: Wow.

00:10:21.310 --> 00:10:23.510
You heard it here first.

00:10:23.510 --> 00:10:29.240
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:10:29.240 --> 00:10:30.540
&gt;&gt; Speaker 2: I think that --

00:10:30.540 --> 00:10:34.510
I feel that I was born
to be doing this today.

00:10:34.510 --> 00:10:40.040
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:43.810
It's really an honor that I can
be here in front of everybody,

00:10:43.810 --> 00:10:45.110
and say the word "Totoro."

00:10:45.110 --> 00:10:47.730
Ask me anything.

00:10:47.730 --> 00:10:49.030
&gt;&gt; Maureen Cohen
Harrington: Okay.

00:10:49.030 --> 00:10:53.620
So you started to
talk about this a bit.

00:10:53.620 --> 00:10:55.330
What is your origin story?

00:10:55.330 --> 00:10:57.360
What led you down
this career path?

00:10:57.360 --> 00:11:01.250
Either personal experiences
or artistic, cultural,

00:11:01.250 --> 00:11:03.510
historical influences?

00:11:03.510 --> 00:11:12.230
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:11:12.230 --> 00:11:18.680
&gt;&gt; Speaker 2: I just watched
a lot of TV when I was little.

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:20.090
&gt;&gt; Maureen Cohen
Harrington: We all do.

00:11:20.090 --> 00:11:22.190
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:11:22.190 --> 00:11:25.280
&gt;&gt; Speaker 2: Then I started
to read books and manga.

00:11:26.510 --> 00:11:36.240
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:39.020
I think it's true for everybody,
but I started to get curious

00:11:39.020 --> 00:11:42.510
about how is this made.

00:11:42.510 --> 00:11:48.220
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:51.400
And then I started to think that
I wanted to be part of that too,

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:53.510
and bring joy to everybody.

00:11:53.510 --> 00:12:03.750
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:06.660
So I went through phases when
I was little that I wanted

00:12:06.660 --> 00:12:09.920
to create movies, I
wanted to create manga,

00:12:09.920 --> 00:12:11.360
and I wanted to write.

00:12:11.360 --> 00:12:12.710
All those things.

00:12:12.710 --> 00:12:14.760
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:23.030
At one point I wanted to create
[inaudible] and "Godzilla."

00:12:23.030 --> 00:12:27.510
And then my friend Anno Hideaki
finally created "Godzilla."

00:12:27.510 --> 00:12:30.510
[ Applause ]

00:12:30.510 --> 00:12:46.000
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.070
&gt;&gt; Speaker 2: And then when I
was eight years old I watched

00:12:48.070 --> 00:12:50.450
"Horus, Price of the
Sun" by Isao Takahata

00:12:50.450 --> 00:12:54.650
and Hayao Miyazaki, and
I wanted to become --

00:12:54.650 --> 00:12:57.510
join the animation industry.

00:12:57.510 --> 00:13:05.050
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:13:05.050 --> 00:13:07.360
So I worked hard so that
I could work side by side

00:13:07.360 --> 00:13:08.660
with these great people.

00:13:08.660 --> 00:13:10.610
And then, 20 years
later, it came true.

00:13:10.610 --> 00:13:12.510
&gt;&gt; Hirokatsu Kihara:
Don't give up.

00:13:12.510 --> 00:13:18.040
[ Applause ]

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:20.310
&gt;&gt; Anthony Dunn:
So you said you --

00:13:20.310 --> 00:13:23.000
How'd you meet Mister Miyazaki?

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.950
Like did you -- You said you
worked hard to get there.

00:13:27.950 --> 00:13:30.990
So how did you like, you
know, actually meet him?

00:13:30.990 --> 00:13:35.510
And become a member
of Studio Ghilbi.

00:13:35.510 --> 00:13:52.910
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:13:52.910 --> 00:13:54.720
&gt;&gt; Speaker 2: So I joined
[inaudible] a company,

00:13:54.720 --> 00:13:56.030
the studio that created
"Nausicaa

00:13:56.030 --> 00:13:57.830
of the Valley of the Wind."

00:13:57.830 --> 00:14:05.040
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:14:05.040 --> 00:14:07.750
I didn't join because it
